# Phase 8 – Release Commit Validation & Compliance Enhancements
## Consolidated Functional Requirements & Acceptance Criteria (Revision 1)

> **Purpose**
>
> This document consolidates all requirements discussed during this phase. Every requirement below is **mandatory** unless explicitly marked as optional. The implementation **must not omit, simplify, or replace** any requirement without explicit approval.

---

# 1. Objective

Enhance the Release Commit Compliance Portal by improving:

- Release commit discovery
- Previous release identification
- Kubernetes integration
- Commit validation
- Trunk-based release validation
- Refresh behavior
- Library handling
- UI improvements
- Performance
- Compliance validations
- Auditability

The implementation must remain backward compatible with the existing implementation until the new approach has been validated.

---

# 2. Background

Our development model is:

- Developers continuously commit code to the **main/master branch**.
- Every Major Release creates a **Release Branch** approximately **14 days before Production Release**.
- Development continues on Main.
- Remaining release stories are merged/cherry-picked into the Release Branch until Release completion.
- Weekly/Bi-weekly releases are performed.

The implementation must support this workflow.

---

# 3. Functional Requirements

---

## FR-1 Generate Report Preconditions

Before enabling **Fetch Stories**, validate the following connections.

Mandatory:

- GitHub Token
- iTrack Token
- At least one Production Kubernetes Cookie
    - Production East
    - OR Production West

If any mandatory connection is unavailable:

- Disable Fetch Stories.
- Clearly indicate which dependency is missing.
- Display user-friendly status indicators.

---

## FR-2 Connection Status Indicators

Display connection status using visual indicators.

Example:

✅ Connected

❌ Not Connected

⚠ Configuration Missing

Do not display technical exceptions directly.

---

## FR-3 Library Identification

Introduce support for Library Components.

Libraries shall be defined through Team Configuration.

Libraries are NOT deployable microservices.

Libraries are dependency artifacts only.

UI must visually differentiate:

- Microservice
- Library

---

## FR-4 Library Processing Rules

Libraries shall:

Participate in:

- Git Commit Analysis
- Story Validation

Skip:

- Kubernetes Deployment Validation
- Deployment Readiness
- Previous Production Version Discovery
- Blue/Green Validation

---

## FR-5 Previous Release Version Resolution

Remove the previous configuration switch.

The system shall always resolve Previous Release Version using the following priority.

Priority 1

Production Kubernetes

↓

Priority 2

Existing Git-based implementation

↓

Priority 3

Leave Previous Release empty for manual selection.

The existing implementation shall remain as a fallback until explicitly removed.

---

## FR-6 Production Deployment Metadata

Retrieve deployment metadata from Kubernetes.

At minimum capture:

- Git Branch
- Git Commit SHA
- Build Number
- Image Tag
- Deployment Timestamp
- Pipeline Information
- Release Version
- Additional deployment labels

Persist all metadata into the database.

---

## FR-7 Kubernetes Metadata Service

Create one reusable service.

Example

KubernetesDeploymentMetadataService

Responsibilities:

- Discover Deployment
- Detect Active Blue/Green
- Read Labels
- Parse Metadata
- Return Common DTO

No duplicate implementations.

---

## FR-8 Release Commit Analysis

Current implementation compares:

Previous Release

↓

Current Release

Continue using this implementation.

Do NOT remove it.

---

## FR-9 Production Commit Anchor

Additionally retrieve:

Production Git Commit SHA.

This commit becomes the deployment anchor.

Initially compare both approaches.

Log differences.

Do not replace the current implementation until validated.

---

## FR-10 Commit Collection Strategy

Collect commits from:

- Release Branch
- Production Deployment Metadata

Validate both.

Compare results.

---

## FR-11 Main Branch Validation

After Release Branch creation:

Developers continue committing to Main.

The implementation shall:

- Analyze Main branch.
- Consider commits after Release Branch creation.
- Filter commits belonging only to Release Stories.

Ignore unrelated commits.

---

## FR-12 Missing Release Commit Detection

If a Release Story contains commits on Main

BUT

those commits are not available in Release Branch

Create Violation.

---

## FR-13 Hard Push / Cherry Pick Support

Correctly handle:

- Cherry Picks
- Direct Release Branch Commits
- Squash Merge (where detectable)
- Rebase (where detectable)

If uncertain

Perform additional history analysis.

---

## FR-14 Commit History Fallback

If Production SHA cannot be found:

Search configurable commit history.

Example:

100 commits backwards.

This value must be configurable.

Never hardcode.

---

## FR-15 Story Filtering

Only Release Stories shall participate.

Ignore commits unrelated to Release Stories.

---

## FR-16 Commit Entity

Treat Commit as Master Data.

Suggested fields:

- SHA
- Repository
- Branch
- Story
- Commit Date
- Author
- Committer
- Source Branch
- Release Branch
- Merge Status
- Validation Status

---

## FR-17 Commit Validation Table

Create separate validation entity.

Store:

- Validation Type
- Override Reason
- Approval
- Admin Decision
- Comments
- Audit History

Never overwrite validation history.

---

## FR-18 Refresh Behaviour

Force Refresh shall update:

- Git metadata
- Story mappings
- Branch mappings
- Repository mappings

Imported metadata shall be refreshed using the latest external data.

---

## FR-19 Preserve Manual Actions

Refresh shall NEVER delete:

- Override Reasons
- Pending Approval
- Approval History
- Admin Decisions
- Comments
- Audit Trail

These shall remain associated using Commit SHA wherever possible.

---

## FR-20 Commit Identity

Commit SHA shall be treated as the primary business identifier.

Never rely solely on Commit Message.

---

## FR-21 Historical Consistency

If a refreshed import no longer contains an imported commit:

Do NOT physically delete it immediately.

Mark it as:

Removed From Latest Import

This preserves auditability.

---

## FR-22 Safe Refresh

Only imported metadata may be refreshed.

Manual workflow information shall never be overwritten.

---

## FR-23 Story Issue Type

While fetching stories from iTrack,

also retrieve the **Issue Type**.

Examples:

- Story
- Bug
- Task
- Epic
- Spike
- Improvement
- Defect
- Any additional supported issue types

Persist the Issue Type in the database.

---

## FR-24 Issue Type UI

Display the Issue Type beside every Story.

Do NOT display large text.

Instead,

display the standard issue icon.

Examples:

🐞 Bug

📖 Story

⚡ Task

⭐ Epic

(or the closest equivalent icon set already used by iTrack/Jira)

The icon shall be:

- Small
- Consistent
- Professional
- Non-intrusive

Hovering the icon shall display the Issue Type name.

---

## FR-25 Violation Categories

Replace generic "Violation".

Introduce categories.

Examples:

- Missing Commit
- Story Not Accepted
- Missing Release Commit
- Branch Validation Failed
- Deployment Validation Failed
- Configuration Difference
- Manual Override Pending
- Unknown

---

## FR-26 Violation Explanation

Every violation shall contain:

- Type
- Description
- Reason
- Suggested Resolution

---

## FR-27 Violation Tooltip

Every violation shall display an Information icon.

Hovering shall explain:

- Why it is a violation.
- Which validation failed.
- Which Story caused it.
- Which Commit caused it.
- Suggested next action.

The explanation must be user-friendly.

---

## FR-28 Performance

Use parallel processing wherever possible.

Preferred:

Spring WebFlux

Flux

Mono

Avoid sequential API processing.

---

## FR-29 Logging

Log execution timing.

Examples:

- Story Fetch
- Component Fetch
- Kubernetes Calls
- Git Calls
- Validation Time
- Total Execution

---

## FR-30 Kubernetes Research

Review Kubernetes documentation.

Document:

- APIs evaluated
- Deployment API
